// Pattern 2: Evidence Chain -- autophagy mechanism argument

<Autophagy Mechanism> #pro

(1) [IF Triggers Autophagy]: de Cabo and Mattson 2019 found that fasting periods activate cellular cleanup via mTOR suppression. #observation
    > "Intermittent fasting stimulates autophagy and mitophagy while inhibiting the mTOR (mammalian target of rapamycin) protein-synthesis pathway."
    [de Cabo & Mattson 2019, NEJM](https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMra1905136)
    {credence: 0.90, reason: "NEJM review, 600+ citations, authoritative"}
(2) [AMPK Drives Autophagy]: AMPK activation under nutrient deprivation directly phosphorylates ULK1 and suppresses mTORC1, initiating autophagy. #observation
    > "AMPK directly phosphorylates ULK, which is a process that is required for ULK1 activation and the initiation of autophagy under nutrient deprivation conditions."
    [Aman et al. 2021, Ageing Research Reviews](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.arr.2021.101400)
    {credence: 0.85, reason: "well-cited review of established molecular pathway"}
(3) [CR Lacks Cycling]: Continuous CR does not produce the same fed/fasted cycling that drives periodic mTOR suppression. #assumption
    {credence: 0.55, reason: "plausible but not directly tested in humans"}
----
(4) IF may activate autophagy pathways more strongly than CR due to periodic deep fasting.
    {inference: 0.50}
  +> [Mechanism Independent]


// Pattern 2: Evidence Chain -- circadian alignment

<Circadian Alignment> #pro

(1) [TRF Circadian]: Longo and Panda 2016 reviewed that time-restricted feeding aligns food intake with circadian metabolic rhythms. #observation
    > "The improvements are attributed to weight loss, reduced inflammation, and alterations in circadian rhythms that favor metabolic health."
    [Longo & Panda 2016, Cell Metabolism](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cmet.2016.06.001)
    {credence: 0.80, reason: "highly cited Cell Metabolism review"}
(2) [Metabolic Switch]: de Cabo and Mattson 2019 describe a metabolic switch from glucose to ketone-based energy during fasting windows. #observation
    > "Evidence is accumulating that eating in a 6-hour period and fasting for 18 hours can trigger a metabolic switch from glucose-based to ketone-based energy."
    [de Cabo & Mattson 2019, NEJM](https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMra1905136)
    {credence: 0.85, reason: "NEJM review, mechanism well-characterized in animal models"}
----
(3) Time-restricted eating provides circadian and metabolic switching benefits that continuous CR does not. 
    {inference: 0.45}
  +> [IF Superior]


