// Pattern 2: Evidence Chain -- meta-analysis shows equivalence

<Meta-Analysis Equivalence> #con

(1) [Isocaloric Meta]: Hamsho et al. 2025 meta-analysis of 20 RCTs found isocaloric IF is not superior to CR on health outcomes. #observation
    > "Isocaloric intermittent fasting (IF) is not superior to calorie restriction (CR) in enhancing health outcomes in adults and the elderly."
    [Hamsho et al. 2025, NMCD](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.numecd.2024.103805)
    {credence: 0.85, reason: "systematic review and meta-analysis of 20 RCTs, GRADE assessment"}
(2) [Benefits CR Dependent]: The same meta-analysis concluded IF benefits are mediated by the caloric deficit, not fasting per se. #observation
    > "The health benefits induced by intermittent fasting are calorie restriction dependent."
    [Hamsho et al. 2025, NMCD](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.numecd.2024.103805)
    {credence: 0.80, reason: "same source, direct conclusion from the meta-analysis"}
----
(3) When calories are matched, IF provides no additional health benefit over CR.
    {inference: 0.80}
  -> [IF Superior]


// Pattern 3: Undercut -- meta-analysis undercuts the autophagy mechanism argument

<Mechanism Not Proven In Humans> #con

(1) [Animal Only]: Most autophagy-longevity evidence comes from yeast, worms, and mice, not human lifespan studies. #assumption
    {credence: 0.80, reason: "well-known translational gap in aging research"}
(2) [Isocaloric Meta]
----
(3) Even if IF activates autophagy more than CR, the RCT evidence shows this does not translate to superior health outcomes.
    {inference: 0.70}
  _> <Autophagy Mechanism>


// Pattern 2: Evidence Chain -- adherence problem

<Adherence Problem> #con

(1) [ADF Dropout]: Trepanowski et al. 2017 RCT found alternate-day fasting had a 38% dropout rate vs 29% for daily caloric restriction. #observation
    > "The dropout rate was highest in the alternate-day fasting group (13 of 34, 38%), relative to the daily calorie restriction group (10 of 35, 29%)."
    [Trepanowski et al. 2017, JAMA Internal Medicine](https://doi.org/10.1001/jamainternmed.2017.0936)
    {credence: 0.80, reason: "12-month RCT published in JAMA, though small sample"}
(2) [Effective Only If Sustained]: Any longevity intervention requires decades of adherence to produce lifespan effects. #assumption
    {credence: 0.90, reason: "obvious requirement for chronic intervention"}
----
(3) Higher dropout rates undermine IF's real-world longevity benefit relative to CR.
    {inference: 0.65}
  -> [Adherence Feasible]


// Pattern 2: Evidence Chain -- no direct longevity data

<No Direct Longevity Data> #con

(1) [CALERIE Biomarkers]: The CALERIE trial showed 25% CR (achieved ~12%) improved aging biomarkers over 2 years, but did not measure actual lifespan. #observation
    > "The CALERIE trial randomized N = 220 nonobese adults to 25% caloric restriction (n = 145; 11.7% caloric restriction was achieved, on average)."
    [Belsky et al. 2017, J Gerontol](https://doi.org/10.1093/gerona/glx146)
    {credence: 0.85, reason: "large well-designed RCT, 214 citations"}
(2) [No IF Lifespan Trial]: No RCT has measured the effect of IF on human lifespan or even multi-year mortality. #observation
    > "Due to the low number of long-term studies, future studies should focus on conducting longitudinal randomized trials comparing IF and CR."
    [Hamsho et al. 2025, NMCD](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.numecd.2024.103805)
    {credence: 0.90, reason: "explicit limitation acknowledged by meta-analysis authors"}
----
(3) Neither IF nor CR has direct human lifespan evidence; the question cannot be definitively answered.
    {inference: 0.85}
  -> [IF Superior]


